Just now

--

Part 1 of the “TypeScript That Scales” series. Every any is a hole in the safety net you installed TypeScript to get.
You adopted TypeScript to catch bugs at compile time. Then you hit a value whose type is annoying to express, the compiler complains, you’re in a hurry, and you type : any. The red squiggle vanishes. Relief. Except you didn't solve the type problem — you told the compiler to stop checking, punching a hole in exactly the safety net you installed TypeScript for. And any spreads: once a value is any, everything it touches loses its types too.
The dirty secret of a lot of “TypeScript” codebases is that they’re JavaScript with any sprinkled on top — all the ceremony of types, none of the protection. Let me show why any is so corrosive and what to reach for instead.
any doesn't mean "any type." It means "turn off type checking for this value and everything it flows into." It's not a type — it's an opt-out of the entire reason you're using TypeScript.
What any Actually Does
any tells the compiler to stop checking. Anything goes, including the bugs TypeScript exists to catch:
let user: any = getUser();
user.nmae; // typo — no error (should be .name)
user.foo.bar.baz; // accessing nonsense — no error
user(); // calling an object — no error
const x: number = user; // assigning object to number — no errorEvery one of those is a bug TypeScript would normally catch. With any, they all sail through to runtime. You're not writing typed code; you've created a checkpoint where the type system is blindfolded.
The Contagion: any Spreads
The worst part is that any doesn't stay contained. Anything derived from an any becomes any too:
const data: any = JSON.parse(response);
const name = data.name; // name is `any`
const upper = name.toUpperCase(); // upper is `any` — still unchecked
processUser(upper); // and now it leaks into processUser...One any at the source quietly disables type-checking across an entire data flow. This is why a few anys can hollow out the type safety of a whole module — they're not local; they propagate.
Fix #1: Use unknown for Truly Unknown Values
When you genuinely don’t know a type (parsing JSON, handling external input), the right tool is unknown, not any. unknown says "I don't know the type yet" — but unlike any, it forces you to check before you use it:
const data: unknown = JSON.parse(response);data.name; // ERROR — must narrow first (this is good!)if (typeof data === "object" && data !== null && "name" in data) {
// now TypeScript knows it's safe
console.log((data as { name: string }).name);
}unknown is the type-safe any: it accepts anything coming in, but won't let you do anything with it until you've proven what it is. That forced check is exactly the safety you wanted. Swap any → unknown and the compiler starts protecting you again.
Fix #2: Actually Describe the Shape
Often any is just laziness avoiding a type that isn't hard to write. Describe the shape and get full checking and autocomplete:
// Instead of: function process(data: any)
interface User {
id: number;
name: string;
email: string;
}
function process(data: User) {
data.nmae; // ERROR caught — the typo can't hide now
}For API responses, define the interface once (or generate it from a schema). The few minutes spent describing the shape pays back every time the compiler catches a typo or a wrong assumption.
Fix #3: When You Must Assert, Do It Narrowly
Sometimes you genuinely know more than the compiler (a value you’ve validated, a DOM element you’re sure exists). A targeted type assertion is acceptable — but keep it narrow and honest:
// Acceptable: a specific, justified assertion at one boundary
const input = document.getElementById("email") as HTMLInputElement;// Better still: validate at the boundary so the type is PROVEN, not asserted
function isUser(x: unknown): x is User {
return typeof x === "object" && x !== null && "id" in x && "name" in x;
}
if (isUser(data)) { /* data is User here, safely */ }A precise assertion at a single boundary is worlds better than blanket any. And a type guard (Part 2) that actually validates is better still, because it proves the type instead of asserting it.
Putting It Together

• any disables type checking for a value and everything it touches — it's an opt-out, not a type.

• Use unknown for genuinely unknown values — it forces a check before use.

• Describe the shape with interfaces instead of reaching for any.

• Assert narrowly at boundaries, or better, validate with a type guard.
The Takeaway
any feels like a convenient escape hatch, but it's really a switch that turns off the one thing TypeScript is for — and because it spreads to everything it touches, a handful of anys can quietly reduce your "typed" codebase back to unchecked JavaScript. The honest tools are right there: unknown for values you don't yet know (it makes you check), real interfaces for shapes you can describe, and narrow assertions or type guards for the rare cases you know more than the compiler. Treat every any as a confession that you skipped the type, hunt them down, and TypeScript goes back to doing its job: catching your bugs before your users do.

This is Part 1 of the TypeScript That Scales series. Next up: narrowing and type guards — how to teach the compiler what you know so it can protect you.
How many anys are hiding in your "TypeScript" codebase right now? 👇
